<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>The <strong>best Bordeaux wines</strong> are legendary for their aging potential, with first-growth châteaux like Lafite, Latour, and Margaux capable of evolving gracefully for 30-50 years or more in exceptional vintages. Left Bank Cabernet Sauvignon-based wines typically require 8-15 years to reach their first drinking window, while Right Bank Merlot-dominant wines from Saint-Émilion and Pomerol often show beautifully after 5-12 years.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>Young Bordeaux displays intense primary fruit—cassis, blackberry, and plum—supported by firm tannins and bright acidity. As the wine ages, <strong>tannins polymerize and soften</strong>, while primary fruit evolves into complex secondary and tertiary aromas: leather, tobacco, cedar, truffle, and graphite. The wine's color shifts from deep purple-ruby to brick-orange at the rim, signaling maturity.</p>

