<h3>Proper Storage</h3>
<p>Store bottles horizontally at <strong>55-58°F (13-14°C)</strong> with 70-75% humidity and minimal vibration. Consistent temperature is crucial—fluctuations cause cork expansion and contraction, leading to premature oxidation.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage Signs</h3>
<p><strong>Proper aging</strong> shows gradual color evolution, integrated tannins, and developing complexity while maintaining fruit balance. <strong>Warning signs include</strong> premature browning, vinegar-like aromas, or complete fruit loss—indicating heat damage, cork failure, or improper storage. A wine showing sediment and brick tones but retaining fruit concentration is likely aging beautifully and ready for careful decanting.</p>

