<p><strong>First Growth Bordeaux</strong> like Lafite, Latour, and Margaux can age gracefully for 30-50+ years, with exceptional vintages like 1982 and 2000 still drinking beautifully today. <strong>Second and Third Growths</strong> typically peak between 15-25 years, while well-made <strong>Cru Bourgeois</strong> wines offer excellent drinking at 8-15 years.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>Young Bordeaux displays bold cassis and blackberry fruit supported by firm tannins from Cabernet Sauvignon. As these wines age, tannins polymerize and soften, while primary fruit transforms into complex secondary notes: leather, tobacco, cedar, and graphite. The legendary "pencil shavings" character of aged Pauillac emerges around year 10-15, while Saint-Julien develops silky elegance and Saint-Estèphe reveals earthy minerality.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p><strong>Left Bank Cabernet Sauvignon-dominant wines</strong> typically need 8-12 years minimum before showing their best, peaking between years 15-25. <strong>Right Bank Merlot-based wines</strong> from Saint-Émilion and Pomerol mature faster, often drinking well at 5-10 years but continuing to evolve for 20+ years in top vintages.</p>

<h3>Proper Storage</h3>
<p>Store bottles horizontally at 55°F (13°C) with 70% humidity and minimal vibration. Bordeaux's dark glass protects against UV, but keep cellars dark. Consistent temperature is more important than perfect temperature.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage Signs</h3>
<p>Properly aged Bordeaux shows brick-red color development at the rim, integrated tannins, and complex aromatics. <strong>Warning signs</strong> include excessive browning throughout, vinegar-like acetic acid, or musty cork taint. Slight sediment is normal and expected in wines over 10 years old.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Left Bank and Right Bank Bordeaux wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Left Bank Bordeaux (including Médoc and Haut-Médoc) are predominantly Cabernet Sauvignon-based with structured tannins and cassis flavors, while Right Bank wines (Saint-Émilion and Pomerol) are mainly Merlot-based with softer, more approachable profiles featuring plum and chocolate notes. Left Bank wines generally age longer and show more minerality from gravel soils, whereas Right Bank wines mature earlier due to clay-limestone terroir. This fundamental difference affects both pricing and drinking windows, with Left Bank typically commanding higher prices for grand cru classé estates.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Bordeaux wines offer the best value under $30?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Cru Bourgeois properties like Château Sociando-Mallet, Château Phélan Ségur, and Château de Pez, which offer excellent quality-to-price ratios typically ranging from $20-30. Saint-Julien and Haut-Médoc appellations often provide exceptional value, as do satellite appellations like Montagne-Saint-Émilion and Lalande-de-Pomerol. Avoid generic Bordeaux AOC wines and instead focus on specific commune appellations, which must meet stricter quality standards and offer more distinctive terroir expression.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibred text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I decant the best Bordeaux wines before serving?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young Bordeaux (under 10 years) benefit from 2-4 hours of decanting to soften tannins and allow full aromatic development, while mature wines (15+ years) should only be decanted 30-60 minutes before serving to preserve delicate flavors. First growth wines and other powerful Left Bank Cabernet Sauvignon blends typically require longer decanting periods than Right Bank Merlot-dominant wines. Always taste periodically during decanting, as some older vintages can fade quickly once exposed to oxygen.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are Bordeaux wines good for beginners, or should I start elsewhere?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Begin with Right Bank Bordeaux wines (Saint-Émilion, Pomerol) or Cru Bourgeois properties, as these tend to be more approachable with softer tannins and immediate fruit appeal compared to austere young Left Bank wines. Avoid first growth Bordeaux as a starting point since these require significant aging and wine knowledge to appreciate fully. Consider starting with well-made Bordeaux from excellent vintages like 2005, 2009, or 2016, which show more generous fruit and integrated tannins even when young.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying expensive Bordeaux?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is buying prestigious names from poor vintages rather than excellent wines from lesser-known producers in great years—a 2013 first growth will disappoint compared to a 2016 Cru Bourgeois. Many buyers also purchase young, tannic Bordeaux without proper storage facilities or patience for 10-20 year aging requirements. Additionally, failing to research drinking windows leads to opening bottles either too early (when harsh and closed) or too late (when past peak), wasting the investment.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which vintages are considered the best for Bordeaux in the last decade?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The standout vintages are 2016 (exceptional balance and aging potential), 2019 (elegant and well-structured), and 2020 (concentrated and powerful) for both Left and Right Bank wines. 2015 and 2014 also produced excellent wines, particularly on the Right Bank where Merlot thrived in the warmer conditions. Avoid 2013 and 2017, which were challenging years with weather issues that resulted in diluted flavors and uneven quality across most châteaux.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I know when my Bordeaux wine is ready to drink?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Check professional drinking windows from critics like James Suckling or Wine Spectator, but also look for physical signs: sediment formation indicates maturity, while harsh tannins that make your mouth pucker suggest more aging is needed. Most classified growth Bordeaux need 8-15 years minimum, with first growths often requiring 15-25 years to reach peak drinking condition. If you must open early, decant for several hours and expect the wine to continue evolving in the glass over 2-3 hours.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good alternatives to expensive Bordeaux first growths?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Consider second growth Left Bank châteaux like Cos d'Estournel, Montrose, or Ducru-Beaucaillou, which offer 80% of the quality at 40% of the price of first growths. For Right Bank alternatives, top Saint-Émilion properties like Canon, Figeac, or Troplong Mondot provide exceptional quality without Cheval Blanc or Ausone pricing. Super Seconds like Pontet-Canet, Lynch-Bages, and Sociando-Mallet consistently outperform their classifications and offer remarkable value for age-worthy Bordeaux.</p>
